      "message": "Hello Nagavarapu,\n\nThank you very much for your time and suggestions!\nI agree with you that I should revise my commit message and make it more clear. I\u0027ll fix it as soon as possible.\n\nBut first, please let me answer your latest comment.\n\nI investigated the BMC-console ipmitool raw path on Romulus. The key finding is that **this command is not received as a System Interface request by phosphor-ipmi-host**. Instead, it is routed through the local D-Bus backend and resolved as `INTRABMC` (channel 8).\n\nThe following part is the details of my investigation.\n\n## Evidence 1: Channel 8\n\nWe can see that after executing `ipmitool raw 0x04 0x02 0x21 0x04 0x01 0x01 0x01 0x59 0x01 0x00`, the debug log of phosphor-ipmi-host showed:\n```\nJun 25 13:30:55 romulus ipmid[310]: PlatformEvent: channel\u003d8, size\u003d8\nJun 25 13:30:55 romulus ipmid[310]: PlatformEvent: data[0]\u003d33\nJun 25 13:30:55 romulus ipmid[310]: PlatformEvent: data[1]\u003d4\nJun 25 13:30:55 romulus ipmid[310]: PlatformEvent: data[2]\u003d1\nJun 25 13:30:55 romulus ipmid[310]: PlatformEvent: data[3]\u003d1\nJun 25 13:30:55 romulus ipmid[310]: PlatformEvent: data[4]\u003d1\nJun 25 13:30:55 romulus ipmid[310]: PlatformEvent: data[5]\u003d89\nJun 25 13:30:55 romulus ipmid[310]: PlatformEvent: data[6]\u003d1\nJun 25 13:30:55 romulus ipmid[310]: PlatformEvent: data[7]\u003d0\n```\n\nThe keypoint is `channel\u003d8`.\n\nAccording to IPMI spec v2.0 Table 6, we can see that channel `0x01` ~ `0x0b` is implementation-specific, and channel `0xf` is reserved for `System Interface`.\n\n## Evidence 2: channel 8 is `INTRABMC` in `channel_config.json`\n\nWe can find the definition of channel 8 on Romulus, and it\u0027s defined as \"INTRABMC\":\n\n```shell\nroot@romulus:~# cat /usr/share/ipmi-providers/channel_config.json\n///\n    \"8\": {\n        \"name\": \"INTRABMC\",\n        \"is_valid\": true,\n        \"active_sessions\": 0,\n        \"channel_info\": {\n            \"medium_type\": \"oem\",\n            \"protocol_type\": \"oem\",\n            \"session_supported\": \"session-less\",\n            \"is_ipmi\": true\n        }\n    },\n///\n```\n\nNext, to investigate why ipmitool on Romulus is interpreted as channel 8, I added the following debug log in `phosphor-ipmi-host/ipmid-new.cpp`:\n\n```diff\ndiff --git a/ipmid-new.cpp b/ipmid-new.cpp\nindex 80c5ced..776d8b3 100644\n--- a/ipmid-new.cpp\n+++ b/ipmid-new.cpp\n@@ -472,18 +472,29 @@ uint8_t channelFromMessage(sdbusplus::message_t\u0026 msg)\n {\n     // channel name for ipmitool to resolve to\n     std::string sender \u003d msg.get_sender();\n+\n+    lg2::info(\"channelFromMessage: sender\u003d{SENDER}\", \"SENDER\", sender);\n+\n     auto chIter \u003d uniqueNameToChannelNumber.find(sender);\n     if (chIter !\u003d uniqueNameToChannelNumber.end())\n     {\n+        lg2::info(\"channelFromMessage: matched sender to channel {CHANNEL}\",\n+                  \"CHANNEL\", chIter-\u003esecond);\n         return chIter-\u003esecond;\n     }\n     // FIXME: currently internal connections are ephemeral and hard to pin down\n     try\n     {\n-        return getChannelByName(intraBmcName);\n+        auto channel \u003d getChannelByName(intraBmcName);\n+        lg2::info(\"channelFromMessage: fallback to {NAME}, channel\u003d{CHANNEL}\",\n+                  \"NAME\", std::string(intraBmcName), \"CHANNEL\", channel);\n+        return channel;\n+        // return getChannelByName(intraBmcName);\n     }\n     catch (const std::exception\u0026 e)\n     {\n+        lg2::error(\"channelFromMessage: failed to resolve {NAME}: {ERROR}\",\n+                   \"NAME\", std::string(intraBmcName), \"ERROR\", std::string(e.what()));\n         return invalidChannel;\n     }\n } // namespace ipmi\n@@ -508,6 +519,15 @@ auto executionEntry(boost::asio::yield_context yield, sdbusplus::message_t\u0026 m,\n \n     // figure out what channel the request came in on\n     uint8_t channel \u003d channelFromMessage(m);\n+\n+    lg2::info(\"executionEntry: sender\u003d{SENDER}, netFn\u003d{NETFN}, cmd\u003d{CMD}, \"\n+          \"lun\u003d{LUN}, channel\u003d{CHANNEL}\",\n+          \"SENDER\", sender,\n+          \"NETFN\", lg2::hex, netFn,\n+          \"CMD\", lg2::hex, cmd,\n+          \"LUN\", lg2::hex, lun,\n+          \"CHANNEL\", channel);\n+\n     if (channel \u003d\u003d invalidChannel)\n     {\n         // unknown sender channel; refuse to service the request\n@@ -550,6 +570,13 @@ auto executionEntry(boost::asio::yield_context yield, sdbusplus::message_t\u0026 m,\n         // ipmb should supply rqSA\n         ChannelInfo chInfo;\n         getChannelInfo(channel, chInfo);\n+\n+        lg2::info(\"executionEntry: channel\u003d{CHANNEL}, mediumType\u003d{MEDIUM}, \"\n+          \"protocolType\u003d{PROTOCOL}\",\n+          \"CHANNEL\", channel,\n+          \"MEDIUM\", static_cast\u003cint\u003e(chInfo.mediumType),\n+          \"PROTOCOL\", static_cast\u003cint\u003e(chInfo.protocolType));\n+\n         if (static_cast\u003cEChannelMediumType\u003e(chInfo.mediumType) \u003d\u003d\n             EChannelMediumType::ipmb)\n         {\n@@ -572,7 +599,7 @@ auto executionEntry(boost::asio::yield_context yield, sdbusplus::message_t\u0026 m,\n         }\n     }\n     // check to see if the requested priv/username is valid\n-    lg2::debug(\"Set up ipmi context: Ch:NetFn/Cmd\u003d{CHANNEL}:{NETFN}/{CMD}\",\n+    lg2::info(\"Set up ipmi context: Ch:NetFn/Cmd\u003d{CHANNEL}:{NETFN}/{CMD}\",\n                \"SENDER\", sender, \"NETFN\", lg2::hex, netFn, \"LUN\", lg2::hex, lun,\n                \"CMD\", lg2::hex, cmd, \"CHANNEL\", channel, \"USERID\", userId,\n                \"SESSIONID\", lg2::hex, sessionId, \"PRIVILEGE\",\n```\n\nThen, I executed the same command, and the result showed that it was interpreted as `INTRABMC`.\n\n```\nJun 25 15:22:59 romulus ipmid[311]: channelFromMessage: sender\u003d:1.66\nJun 25 15:22:59 romulus ipmid[311]: channelFromMessage: fallback to INTRABMC, channel\u003d8\nJun 25 15:22:59 romulus ipmid[311]: executionEntry: sender\u003d:1.66, netFn\u003d0x2c, cmd\u003d0x0, lun\u003d0x0, channel\u003d8\nJun 25 15:22:59 romulus ipmid[311]: executionEntry: channel\u003d8, mediumType\u003d96, protocolType\u003d28\nJun 25 15:22:59 romulus ipmid[311]: Set up ipmi context: Ch:NetFn/Cmd\u003d8:0x2c/0x0\nJun 25 15:22:59 romulus ipmid[311]: channelFromMessage: sender\u003d:1.66\nJun 25 15:22:59 romulus ipmid[311]: channelFromMessage: fallback to INTRABMC, channel\u003d8\nJun 25 15:22:59 romulus ipmid[311]: executionEntry: sender\u003d:1.66, netFn\u003d0x2c, cmd\u003d0x0, lun\u003d0x0, channel\u003d8\nJun 25 15:22:59 romulus ipmid[311]: executionEntry: channel\u003d8, mediumType\u003d96, protocolType\u003d28\nJun 25 15:22:59 romulus ipmid[311]: Set up ipmi context: Ch:NetFn/Cmd\u003d8:0x2c/0x0\nJun 25 15:22:59 romulus ipmid[311]: channelFromMessage: sender\u003d:1.66\nJun 25 15:22:59 romulus ipmid[311]: channelFromMessage: fallback to INTRABMC, channel\u003d8\nJun 25 15:22:59 romulus ipmid[311]: executionEntry: sender\u003d:1.66, netFn\u003d0x4, cmd\u003d0x2, lun\u003d0x0, channel\u003d8\nJun 25 15:22:59 romulus ipmid[311]: executionEntry: channel\u003d8, mediumType\u003d96, protocolType\u003d28\nJun 25 15:22:59 romulus ipmid[311]: Set up ipmi context: Ch:NetFn/Cmd\u003d8:0x4/0x2\n```\n\n## Evidence 3: The `ipmitool raw ...` command on Romulus sends request to local D-Bus\n\nI originally thought the ipmitool command was sent to `/dev/ipmi-bt-host` becuase this device exists on Romulus. To test this idea, I:\n1. Stop btbridge `systemctl stop org.openbmc.HostIpmi`\n2. Execute the same ipmitool command\n\nSurprisingly, the ipmitool command still worked, which means the ipmitool on Romulus doesn\u0027t go to btbridge.\n\nNext, I executed `busctl monitor xyz.openbmc_project.Ipmi.Host` on Romulus and executed the same ipmitool command in another terminal connected to Romulus. One message is captured:\n\n```\n\u003e Type\u003dmethod_call  Endian\u003dl  Flags\u003d0  Version\u003d1 Cookie\u003d4  Timestamp\u003d\"Thu 2026-06-25 16:10:18.320005 UTC\"\n  Sender\u003d:1.79  Destination\u003dxyz.openbmc_project.Ipmi.Host  Path\u003d/xyz/openbmc_project/Ipmi  Interface\u003dxyz.openbmc_project.Ipmi.Server  Member\u003dexecute\n  UniqueName\u003d:1.79\n  MESSAGE \"yyyaya{sv}\" {\n          BYTE 4;\n          BYTE 0;\n          BYTE 2;\n          ARRAY \"y\" {\n                  BYTE 33;\n                  BYTE 4;\n                  BYTE 1;\n                  BYTE 1;\n                  BYTE 1;\n                  BYTE 89;\n                  BYTE 1;\n                  BYTE 0;\n          };\n          ARRAY \"{sv}\" {\n          };\n  };\n```\n\nThe result showed that the `ipmitool raw ...` command seem to be sent by directly calling the following D-Bus method rather than going to the btbridge.\n\n```\nxyz.openbmc_project.Ipmi.Host\n/xyz/openbmc_project/Ipmi\nxyz.openbmc_project.Ipmi.Server.execute()\n```\n\nThen, I searchd the ipmitool source code and found out it contains code that can call the D-Bus method:\n\n```\n~/openbmc/build/romulus/workspace/sources/ipmitool/src (devtool)$ grep -nr openbmc ./*\n./plugins/dbus/dbus.c:55:\tstatic const char *destination \u003d \"xyz.openbmc_project.Ipmi.Host\";\n./plugins/dbus/dbus.c:56:\tstatic const char *object_path \u003d \"/xyz/openbmc_project/Ipmi\";\n./plugins/dbus/dbus.c:57:\tstatic const char *interface \u003d \"xyz.openbmc_project.Ipmi.Server\";\n./plugins/dbus/dbus.c:103:\t/* The D-Bus xyz.openbmc_project.Ipmi.Server.execute interface\n```\n\nTo prove my thought, I added the following debug log in `ipmitool/src/plugins/dbus/dbus.c` and executed the same ipmitool command.\nThe result showed that, yes, the ipmitool send the ipmi request by calling the D-Bus method.\n\n```\ndiff --git a/src/plugins/dbus/dbus.c b/src/plugins/dbus/dbus.c\nindex be72dcb..90db565 100644\n--- a/src/plugins/dbus/dbus.c\n+++ b/src/plugins/dbus/dbus.c\n@@ -97,6 +97,9 @@ ipmi_dbus_sendrecv(struct ipmi_intf *intf,\n        rsp.data_len \u003d 0;\n        memset(rsp.data, 0, sizeof(rsp.data));\n \n+    fprintf(stderr, \"ipmitool dbus plugin: calling %s %s %s.%s\\n\",\n+        destination, object_path, interface, method_name);\n+\n        /* The D-Bus xyz.openbmc_project.Ipmi.Server.execute interface\n         * looks like this:\n         *\n@@ -116,6 +119,17 @@ ipmi_dbus_sendrecv(struct ipmi_intf *intf,\n        rc \u003d sd_bus_message_new_method_call(bus, \u0026request, destination,\n                                            object_path, interface,\n                                            method_name);\n+\n+    fprintf(stderr, \"ipmitool dbus plugin: netfn\u003d0x%02x lun\u003d0x%02x cmd\u003d0x%02x data_len\u003d%d\\n\",\n+        req-\u003emsg.netfn, req-\u003emsg.lun, req-\u003emsg.cmd, req-\u003emsg.data_len);\n+\n+    fprintf(stderr, \"ipmitool dbus plugin: payload\u003d\");\n+    for (int i \u003d 0; i \u003c req-\u003emsg.data_len; ++i)\n+    {\n+        fprintf(stderr, \" %02x\", req-\u003emsg.data[i]);\n+    }\n+    fprintf(stderr, \"\\n\");\n+\n        if (rc \u003c 0) {\n                lprintf(LOG_ERR, \"%s: failed to create message: %s\\n\",\n                        __func__, strerror(-rc));\n```\n\nResult:\n\n```\nroot@romulus:~# ipmitool raw 0x04 0x02 0x21 0x04 0x01 0x01 0x01 0x59 0x01 0x00\nipmitool dbus plugin: calling xyz.openbmc_project.Ipmi.Host /xyz/openbmc_project/Ipmi xyz.openbmc_project.Ipmi.Server.execute\nipmitool dbus plugin: netfn\u003d0x2c lun\u003d0x00 cmd\u003d0x00 data_len\u003d1\nipmitool dbus plugin: payload\u003d 00\nipmitool dbus plugin: calling xyz.openbmc_project.Ipmi.Host /xyz/openbmc_project/Ipmi xyz.openbmc_project.Ipmi.Server.execute\nipmitool dbus plugin: netfn\u003d0x2c lun\u003d0x00 cmd\u003d0x00 data_len\u003d1\nipmitool dbus plugin: payload\u003d 03\nipmitool dbus plugin: calling xyz.openbmc_project.Ipmi.Host /xyz/openbmc_project/Ipmi xyz.openbmc_project.Ipmi.Server.execute\nipmitool dbus plugin: netfn\u003d0x04 lun\u003d0x00 cmd\u003d0x02 data_len\u003d8\nipmitool dbus plugin: payload\u003d 21 04 01 01 01 59 01 00\nUnable to send RAW command (channel\u003d0x0 netfn\u003d0x4 lun\u003d0x0 cmd\u003d0x2 rsp\u003d0xc7): Request data length invalid\nroot@romulus:~#\n```\n\n## Conclusion\n\nSo we can see that the path of the ipmitool command on Romulus is:\n\n```\nipmitool -\u003e D-Bus -\u003e phosphor-ipmi-host\n```\n\nThere\u0027s no any system interface involved in the path, and it is interpreted as `INTRABMC` in phosphor-ipmi-host.\n\nTherefore, the command\n```\nipmitool raw 0x04 0x02 0x21 0x04 0x01 0x01 0x01 0x59 0x01 0x00\n```\non Romulus is not exercising the System Interface parsing path.\n\nThe previous implementation accepted this payload only because\n`isFromSystemChannel()` always returned `true`, so every request was\nparsed as System Interface format.\n\nWith this patch, payload decoding is selected based on the actual\nincoming channel rather than always assuming the System Interface\nformat. Therefore, an 8-byte System Interface payload is rejected when\nreceived through INTRABMC.\n\nI hope this finding solve your question ^^.\nPlease let me know if you think I have misunderstood the request path or if there is another scenario that you would like me to verify.",
